# Amazon RDS Overview

* RDS stands for Relational Database Service
* it's a managed DB service for DB use SQL as a query language
* it allows you to create database in the cloud that are managed by AWS
    * Postgres
    * MySQL
    * MariaDB
    * Oracle
    * Microsoft SQL Server
    * IBM DB2
    * Aurora (AWS Proprietary database [AWS专有数据库])
## advantage [优势] over using RDS versus [相对] deploying DB on EC2

* RDS is a managed [托管] service :
    * automated provisioning ,OS patching [自动配置、操作系统补丁]
    * continuous  backups and restore to specific timestamp[持续备份和恢复到特定的时间戳] (point in time restore [时间点恢复])
    * monitoring dashboards 
    * read replicas [副本] for improved read performance
    * **multi AZ setup for DR (disaster recovery [灾难恢复])**
    * maintenance window for upgrades [升级维护窗口]
    * scaling capability (vertical and horizontal)
    * storage backed [支持] by EBS (gp2 or io1)
* but you can't SSH into your instances
## RDS - Storage Auto Scaling

* helps you increase storage on your RDS DB instance dynamically
* when RDS detects [检测] you are running out of [快用完] free database storage, it scales automatically
* avoid [避免] manually [手动] scaling your database storage
* you have to set **Maximum Storage Threshold [阈值]**(maximum limit for DB storage)
* automatically modify [修改] storage if :
    * free storage [可用存储] is less than 10% of allocated [分配] storage
    * low-storage lasts [持续] at least 5 minutes
    * 6 hour have passed since last modification
* useful for application with**unpredicatable workloads [不可预测的负载]**
* supports all RDS database engines
![图片](data:image/png;base64,)


##  RDS Read Replicas for read scalability

You can not create encrypted Read Replicas from an unencrypted RDS DB instance.

* up to 15 read replicas
* within AZ, cross AZ or cross region
* replication [复制] is **ASYNC**, so read are eventually [最终地] consistent [一致的]
* replicas can be promoted [提升] to their own DB
* applications must update the connection string to leverage read replicas [应用程序必须更新连接字符串才能利用只读副本]
![图片](data:image/png;base64,)


### Use Cases

*  you have a production database that is taking on normal load
* you want to run a reporting application to run some analytics
* you create a Read Replica to run the new workload there
* the production application is unaffected
* read replicas are used for  SELECT(= read) only kind of statements [陈述] (not INSERT, UPDATE,DELETE)
![图片](data:image/png;base64,)



### Network Cost

A Read Replica in a different AWS Region than the source database can be used as a standby database and promoted to become the new production database in case of a regional disruption. So, we'll have a highly available (because of Multi-AZ) RDS DB Instance in the destination AWS Region with both read and write available.

* in AWS there's a network cost when data goes from one AZ to another
* **For RDS Read Replicas within the same region, you don't pay that fee**
![图片](data:image/png;base64,)


## RDS Multi AZ (Disaster Recovery)

Multi-AZ keeps the same connection string regardless of which database is up.

* **SYNC**replication
* one DNS name - automatic app failover to standby [自动应用程序故障转移到待机状态]
* increase **availability**
* failover [故障转移] in case of loss of AZ, loss of network , instance or storage failure
* no manual intervention [干涉] in apps
* not used for scaling
* **Note**: the read replicas be setup as Multi AZ for Disaster Recovery (DR)
![图片](data:image/png;base64,)


## RDS- From Single -AZ to Multi - AZ

* Zero downtime  operation [0停机时间](no need to stop the DB)
* just click on "modify [修改]" for the database
* the following happens internally [内部] :
    * a snapshot is taken
    * a new DB is restored from the snapshot in a new AZ
    * **synchronization**[同步] is established between the two database
![图片](data:image/png;base64,)


**Read Replica uses Asynchronous Replication and Multi-AZ uses Synchronous Replication**

# Amazon Aurora

* Aurora is a proprietary [专有] technology from AWS (not open source)
* Postgres and MySQL are both supported as Aurora DB (that means your drivers will work as if Aurora was a Postgres or MySQL database)
* Aurora is "AWS cloud optimized [优化]" and claim [宣称] 5x performance improvement over MySQL on RDS, over 3x the performance of Postgres on RDS
* Aurora storage automatically grows in increments [增量] of 10GB,up to 127TB.
* Aurora can have up to 15 replicas and the replication process is faster than MySQL (sub 10 ms replicas lag [副本延迟低于10s])
* failover [故障转移] in Aurora is instantaneous[瞬间] . it's HA native
* Aurora costs more than RDS (20% more) - but is more effcient [高效]
## Aurora High Availability and Read Scaling

* 6 copies of your data across 3 AZ:
    * 4 copies out of 6 needed for writes [写入需要6个副本中的4个]
    * 3 copies out of 6 need for reads [读取需要6个副本中的3个]
    * self healing [自我修复] with peer-to-peer [点对点] replication
    * storage is striped across 100s of volumes [存储跨数百个卷进行条带化]
* one Aurora instance takes writes (master)
* automated failover for master in less than 30 seconds
* master + up to **15 Aurora Read Replicas**serve reads [master 上最多拥有15个读取副本]
* support for Cross Region Replication

## Features of Aurora

* automatic fail-over
* backup and recovery
* isolation and security
* industry  compliance [行业合规]
* push-button scaling
* automated patching [修补] with zero Downtime [自动修补，0停机时间]
* advanced [先进的] monitoring
* routine [例行] maintenance  [例行维持]
* backtrack [回溯] : restore data at any point of time without using backups
# RDS & Aurora Security 

* **At-rest [静态] encryption:**
    * database master & replicas encryption using AWS KMS - must be defined as launch time
    * if the master is not encrypted. the read replicas cannot be encrypted
    * to encrypt an un-encrypted database , go through [查看] a DB snapshot & restore as encrypted
* **in-flight encryption:** TLS-ready by default, use the AWS TLS root certificates client-side
* **IAM authentication :** IAM roles to connect to your database (instead of username/pw)
* **Security Groups :**control network access to your RDS / Aurora DB
* **No SSH available** except on RDS Custom
* **Audit [审核] logs can be enabled** and sent to CloudWatch Logs for longer retention [保留]
# Amazon RDS Proxy

* fully managed database proxy for RDS
* allows apps to pool [汇总]and share DB connections established with the database
* **improving database efficiency by reducing the stress on database resources (eg, CPU,RAM) and minimize open connections (and timeouts)**
* serverless,autoscaling ,highly available (multi-AZ)
* **reduced RDS & Aurora failover time by up 66%**
* supports RDS (MySQL,PostgreSQL,MariaDB,MS SQL Server) and Aurora (MySQL,PostgreSQL)
* no code changes required for most apps
* **enforce IAM authentication for DB, and securely store credentials [凭证] in AWS Secrets Manager**
* **RDS proxy is never publicly accessible (must be accessed from VPC)**

# Amazon ElastiCache Overview

Storing Session Data in ElastiCache is a common pattern to ensuring different EC2 instances can retrieve your user's state if needed.

ElastiCache and RDS Read Replicas do indeed help with scaling reads.

* the same way RDS is to get managed Relational Databases [与 RDS 获取托管关系数据库的方式相同..].....
* ElasticCache is to get managed Redis or Memcached
* Cache are in-memory [内存] databases with really high performance, low latency
* helps reduce load off [负载] of database for read intensive workloads
* helps make your application stateless
* AWS takes care of OS maintenance / patching [修补],optimizations,setup,configuration, monitoring,failure recovery and backups
* **Using ElasticCache involves heavy application code changes**
## ElastiCache Solution Architecture

### DB Cache

* application queries ElastiCache , if not available, get from RDS and store in ElastiCache
* helps relieve [缓解] load in RDS
* Cache must have an invalidation strategy [失效策略] to make sure only the most current data [最新的数据] is used in there
![图片](data:image/png;base64,)


### User Session Store

* user logs into any of the application
* the application writes the session data into ElastiCache
* the user hits another instance of our application
* the instance retrieves [检索] the data and the user is already logger in
![图片](data:image/png;base64,)


## Redis vs Memcached

### REDIS

* **Multi AZ**with Auto-Failover
* **Read Replicas** to scale reads and have **high availability**
* data durability [持久性] using AOF persistence
* **backup and restore features**
* supports Sets and Sorted Sets
![图片](data:image/png;base64,)


### MEMCACHED

* Multi-node for partitioning [分区] of data(sharding [分片])
* **No high availability (replication)**
* **Non persistent [不持久]**
* **No backup and restore**
* Multi-threaded architecture
![图片](data:image/png;base64,)


# Caching Implementation [实现] Considerations [注意事项]

* **Is it safe to cache data ?**
    * data may be out of date [过时], eventually consistent [最终一致]
* **Is caching effective for that data ?**
    *  pattern [模式]: data changing slowly, few keys are frequently needed
    * Anti pattern [反模式]: data changing rapidly [迅速地], all large key space frequently needed
* Is data structured well for caching ?
    * example : key value caching, or caching of aggregations [聚合] results
## ElastiCache Strategies [策略]

### Lazy Loading / Cache-Aside / Lazy Population

Lazy Loading would load data into the cache only when necessary (actively requested data from the database).

![图片](data:image/png;base64,)


* Pros [优点]
    * only requested data is cached (the cache isn't filled up with unused data)
    * node failures are not fatal [致命的] (just increased latency to warm the cache)
* Cons [缺点]
    * Cache miss penalty [未命中] that results in 3 round trips [往返], noticeable [明显的] delay for that request
#### Python Pseudocode [伪代码]

![图片](data:image/png;base64,)


### Write Through - Add or Update cache when database is updated

![图片](data:image/png;base64,)


* Pros:
    * data in cache is never stale [过时], **reads are quick**
    * **write penalty**[写入] vs read penalty (each write requires 2 calls)
* Cons
    * missing data until it is added/updated in the DB . Mitigation [缓解措施]  is to implement [实施] Lazy Loading strategy as well
    * Cache churn [缓存搅动]- a lot of the data will never be read

## Cache Evictions [驱逐] and Time-to-live [生存时间] (TTL)

* cache eviction can occur in three ways :
    * you delete the item explicitly [明确地] in the cache
    * item is evicted because the memory is full and it's not recently uesed (LRU)
    * you set an item **time-to-live (or TTL)**
* TTL are helpful for any kind of data
    * leaderboards [排行榜]
    * comments [评论]
    * activity streams [活动流]
* TTL can range from few seconds to hours or days
* if too many evictions happen due to memory, you should scale up or out
## Final words of wisdom [智慧]

* Lazy Loading / Cache aside is easy to implement and works for many situations [情况] as a foundation, especially on the read side
* Write-through is usually combined with Lazy Loading as targeted for the queries or workloads that benefit from this optimization
* setting a TTL is usually not a bad idea, except when you're using Write-through. set it to a sensible [合理] value for your application
* only cache the data that makes sense [只缓存有意义的数据] (user profiles, blogs, etc...)
* *Quote [引用] ：there are only two hard things in Computer Science : cache invalidation [失效] and naming things*
